5.10 Phase Space Trajectory**
The relation between position and conjugate momentum for the given value of energy is dened as phase curve.
5.10.1 Properties of phase space
(i) For time-independent Hamiltonians, the phase curves never intersect each other.
(ii) Phase curve may be closed, open or unbounded curve.
(iii) Classical phase curve means we are plotting the phase curve for the given energy E.
(iv) The state of classical mechanical system is precisely determined since there is not any uncertainty principle in CM.
(v) The path of classical phase trajectory is well dened.
(vi) For the system with n degrees of freedom, the phase space will be 2n-dimensional.
5.10.2 Steps to draw phase-space trajectory
(i) Draw the potential in which the particle is moving
(ii) Draw classically allowed lines (E V (x)). Among the lines, mark the special cases E < 0, E > 0 and E = 0 including
maxima and minima of V (x). Among the marked lines, mark the region where E V (x).
(iii) Project the potentials in the x p
x
plane. The projection of closed region with stable equilibrium point gives closed loop.
Unclosed region or decreasing potential gives parabolic or hyperbolic type graph.
(iv) The phase trajectories follow the directions given below.
(v) Diagram will be symmetric about X-axis ignoring direction.
(vi) If V (x) even, the trajectory will be symmetric about both X and Y-axis ignoring the direction.
